hamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","England":"England"},"cs":{"1375–1450":"1375–1450","1400–1470":"1400–1470","1400":"1400","1375":"1375","about 1400":"okolo 1400","1450":"1450","1382":"1382","1470":"1470","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, Anglie","England":"Anglie"},"da":{"1375–1450":"1375–1450","1400–1470":"1400–1470","1400":"1400","1375":"1375","about 1400":"omkring 1400","1450":"1450","1382":"1382","1470":"1470","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","England":"England"},"nl":{"1375–1450":"1375–1450","1400–1470":"1400–1470","1400":"1400","1375":"1375","about 1400":"circa 1400","1450":"1450","1382":"1382","1470":"1470","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","England":"England"},"en":{"1375–1450":"1375–1450","1400–1470":"1400–1470","1400":"1400","1375":"1375","about 1400":"about 1400","1450":"1450","1382":"1382","1470":"1470","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Williams","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   William  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This form of the surname is also common in Wales. In North America, this surname has also absorbed some cognates from other languages, such as Dutch   Willems  . <i>Williams</i> is the third most frequent surname in the US. It is also very common among African Americans and Native Americans.","History: This surname was brought to North America from southern England and Wales independently by many different bearers from the 17th century onward. Roger Williams, born in London in 1603, came to MA in 1630, but the clergyman was banished from the colony for his criticism of the Puritan government; he fled to RI and founded Providence."],"variants":[{"name":"Wiliams","meanings":["(1997: 124;2007: 828; 2010: NA)","English and Welsh: variant of   Williams  ."]},{"name":"Willams","meanings":["(1997: 223;2007: 1220; 2010: NA)","English: variant of   Williams  ."]},{"name":"Willimas","meanings":["Altered form of English   Williams  ."]},{"name":"William","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Middle English personal name <i>William</i>, <i>Willam</i>, <i>Willem</i>, an Old Picard and Norman French form of ancient Germanic <i>Willihelm</i>, composed of the elements <i>wil-</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm-</i> ‘helmet, protection’. This Norman personal name became widely used in England, Scotland and Wales after the Conquest, mainly no doubt in honor of the Conqueror himself. By the 13th century it had already become the most popular personal name in England. A Parisian form of the name <i>Guillaume</i> was also sometimes used (see   Gillam  ), which in medieval Wales was adopted as <i>Gwilym</i> (see   Gwilliam  ).","Americanized form (translation into English) of French   Guillaume  ."]},{"name":"Pulliam","meanings":["Welsh and English: Anglicized form of Welsh <i>ap William</i> ‘son of William’ (see   Williams  ). This surname is very rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Willaims","meanings":["Altered form of English   Williams  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":7,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"William Williams was born in 1375, in Buckinghamshire, England. He had at least 1 daughter with Elizabeth Field. He died in 1450, in his hometown, at the age of 75."},"et":{"1375–1450":"1375–1450","1400–1470":"1400–1470","1400":"1400","1375":"1375","about 1400":"umbes 1400","1450":"1450","1382":"1382","1470":"1470","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","England":"England"},"fi":{"1375–1450":"1375–1450","1400–1470":"1400–1470","1400":"1400","1375":"1375","about 1400":"noin 1400","1450":"1450","1382":"1382","1470":"1470","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","England":"England"},"fr":{"1375–1450":"1375–1450","1400–1470":"1400–1470","1400":"1400","1375":"1375","about 1400":"environ 1400","1450":"1450","1382":"1382","1470":"1470","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, Angleterre","England":"Angleterre","lifeSummary":"William Williams est né en 1375, à Buckinghamshire, Angleterre. Il a eu au moins 1 fille avec Elizabeth Field. Il est décédé en 1450, dans sa ville natale, à l’âge de 75 ans."},"de":{"1375–1450":"1375–1450","1400–1470":"1400–1470","1400":"1400","1375":"1375","about 1400":"um 1400","1450":"1450","1382":"1382","1470":"1470","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","England":"England","lifeSummary":"William Williams wurde 1375 in Buckinghamshire, England geboren. Er hatte mit Elizabeth Field mindestens 1 Tochter. Er starb 1450 im Alter von 75 Jahren in seinem Geburtsort."},"ht":{"1375–1450":"1375–1450","1400–1470":"1400–1470","1400":"1400","1375":"1375","about 1400":"about 1400","1450":"1450","1382":"